static?
This map is inside an unnamed namespace so I'm pretty sure the `static` is redundant here as it's supposed to be the C++ replacement for it.
Ah, good point. Guess the static on line 40 should be dropped (that's not your concern though).
Done

Ah, so before we stabilise e.g. `decode_get_state_effecter_states_resp()`, do you mind changing the affected functions to return 0 or negative errno values? I want to get away from the library API relying on PLDM protocol completion codes (... but obviously the completion code in the decode message needs to remain a PLDM completion code).
Done
Mildly surprised that this is how the data should be represented (and not embedding a list in the json?), but I'm not a maintainer of the PLDM repo 😊
I was kind of surprised by that too to be honest.
Done
This doesn't seem right 😊
Oops, was blinded by too much C lately, fixed.
The code look good. I just have some minor comment.
`PLDM_SUCCESS` is 0 . So how about `if (rc || resp.completion_code)`?

I actually wanted to explicitly state PLDM_SUCCESS for readability because it's not obvious that it's 0.

If you think otherwise I don't mind changing it.
Done

This is not lg2::error. But can we avoid to use anti-pattern? https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/anti-patterns.md#ill-defined-data-structuring-in-lg2-message-strings

```
std::cerr << "Response Message Error: "
          << "return code " << rc
          << ",completion code " << static_cast<int>(resp.completion_code)
          << std::ends;
```

From what I understand from this doc, the reason this is an anti-pattern in lg2 is because the journal keeps some metadata about the log message.
 
This is not the case in stderr so I think it's not an anti-pattern here.
Done
Use c++ type cast.
Done

Use `Range_based`.
```
for (const auto& i :
         std::views::iota(0, static_cast<int>(resp.comp_effecter_count)))
```
Done
Please check the build error.
Look good to me.
